it comes to content.

3
00:00:07.048 --> 00:00:11.209
Now, a priming is about
preparing the user for

4
00:00:11.209 --> 00:00:15.265
the offering you
are presenting them with and

5
00:00:15.265 --> 00:00:18.908
it's about, it can be used in a bad way.

6
00:00:18.908 --> 00:00:23.120
So, for example,
if you've ever watched any Darren Brown,

7
00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:25.884
who does like mind tricks, and people.

8
00:00:25.884 --> 00:00:27.365
He's a magician, right?

9
00:00:27.365 --> 00:00:30.643
He can set them up with
certain key things,

10
00:00:30.643 --> 00:00:34.844
that they see certain objects in a room or
key phrases.

11
00:00:34.844 --> 00:00:38.795
And he can influence the decision they
make in quite a manipulative way and

12
00:00:38.795 --> 00:00:42.956
that he's using priming to do that,
the fact that we're quite influenced.

13
00:00:42.956 --> 00:00:46.976
But priming can also be used
in a very positive way,

14
00:00:46.976 --> 00:00:53.334
to make the people feel comfortable in a
situation and make people feel valued and

15
00:00:53.334 --> 00:00:59.600
a product is right for them and
is in line with their way of doing things.

16
00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:04.570
And a lot of this comes down to how you
word things and even the imagery you pick.

17
00:01:04.570 --> 00:01:08.327
So let me give you a couple of
examples to show what I mean.

18
00:01:08.327 --> 00:01:12.460
The first example is around something
called mental models, right?

19
00:01:13.700 --> 00:01:17.090
This is the big promo, and
I'm sure you've come across this before.

20
00:01:17.090 --> 00:01:19.866
Where a client is designing a website or

21
00:01:19.866 --> 00:01:24.333
creating a new website with you and
you're working with them.

22
00:01:24.333 --> 00:01:26.991
And they're creating
the information architecture and

23
00:01:26.991 --> 00:01:29.987
they start using jargon and
phrases that don't make any sense.

24
00:01:29.987 --> 00:01:34.608
And you tell them that they shouldn't
put it in, and they say, but

25
00:01:34.608 --> 00:01:36.779
everybody knows those phrases.

26
00:01:36.779 --> 00:01:41.240
Well, what's happened there
is that their mental model,

27
00:01:41.240 --> 00:01:45.971
their way of seeing and
perceiving the world has kind of left and

28
00:01:45.971 --> 00:01:51.290
is no longer in line with
the mental model of their audience.

29
00:01:51.290 --> 00:01:53.408
And this happens for a couple of reasons.

30
00:01:53.408 --> 00:01:59.776
One is because, they're having
a unique perspective on things.

31
00:01:59.776 --> 00:02:03.196
That we all have different
ways of seeing the world and

32
00:02:03.196 --> 00:02:07.385
structuring information that's
influenced by our situation.

33
00:02:07.385 --> 00:02:11.490
So there's a very famous fable about
an elephant and you get a group of blind

34
00:02:11.490 --> 00:02:15.087
people that are all introduced to
an elephant for the first time.

35
00:02:15.087 --> 00:02:19.989
And one of them starts off by touching
the elephant's leg and it concludes that

36
00:02:19.989 --> 00:02:24.156
the elephant must be a tree from
because it feels like a tree trunk.

37
00:02:24.156 --> 00:02:26.459
Another one touches the elephant tail and

38
00:02:26.459 --> 00:02:29.362
concludes it's a rope
because it feels like a rope.

39
00:02:29.362 --> 00:02:35.640
Another one touches the trunk and thinks
that the elephant is a snake and so on.

40
00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:39.920
So our experiences kind of
alter how we see the world.

41
00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:45.794
So you need to be very aware of how your
audience sees the world, how they think of

42
00:02:45.794 --> 00:02:49.929
things, how they structure things and
use appropriate language.

43
00:02:49.929 --> 00:02:54.386
But to make matters worse, there's
something called the expert dilemma,

44
00:02:54.386 --> 00:02:57.728
which is the more knowledgeable
you become in a subject,

45
00:02:57.728 --> 00:03:02.135
the more your way of seeing the world
differs from your audiences, right?

46
00:03:02.135 --> 00:03:07.830
And that's why people that, you know,
running projects are the worst people

47
00:03:07.830 --> 00:03:13.278
to be writing the content and creating
the navigational structure for it.

48
00:03:13.278 --> 00:03:17.590
Because they're experts in the product,
and so they don't really understand it.

49
00:03:18.590 --> 00:03:22.550
So to give you a real life
example of this, okay?

50
00:03:22.550 --> 00:03:27.289
I'm gonna give you a phrase,
Jill is going to the bank.

51
00:03:27.289 --> 00:03:31.511
What is Jill going to do,
is my question for you.

52
00:03:31.511 --> 00:03:36.561
I'm expecting to see things
like going to withdraw money or

53
00:03:36.561 --> 00:03:42.670
going to pay a bill or
someone always says to rob a bank, right?

54
00:03:42.670 --> 00:03:47.231
But they'll almost all be something
to do with financial transactions

55
00:03:47.231 --> 00:03:50.620
because that's what you think of,
isn't it?

56
00:03:50.620 --> 00:03:52.110
Jill is going to the bank.

57
00:03:53.750 --> 00:03:58.328
But not everybody necessarily
will have that kind of worldview.

58
00:03:58.328 --> 00:04:02.468
If you are a keen angler, or
if you like to do sailing or

59
00:04:02.468 --> 00:04:07.720
